**Hypothesis:**  
We hypothesize that metalloid-based MOFs (e.g., boron/silicon-organic frameworks) with dual-enzyme mimetic activity—specifically peroxidase-like (to generate •OH from H₂O₂) and catalase-like (to decompose H₂O₂ into O₂)—can self-replenish oxygen *in situ* while sustaining Fenton-like reactions in the hypoxic tumor microenvironment. This cascade creates a localized oxidative storm, selectively amplifying oxidative stress in tumors via synergistic ROS generation and oxygen cycling, thereby overcoming therapeutic resistance associated with hypoxia. The metalloid nodes’ tunable Lewis acidity and redox-active defects are critical for enhancing catalytic turnover and substrate specificity.  

**Testability:**  
(1) Validate O₂ self-supply via dissolved oxygen probes;  
(2) Quantify •OH production using EPR and fluorescent probes;  
(3) Assess cytotoxicity in 3D tumor spheroids under normoxia vs. hypoxia;  
(4) Characterize defect-driven catalysis through XPS and DFT simulations.
